**Comment System Function**
==========================

Below is an example of a JavaScript function that allows users to comment on a post. This example uses HTML for the front-end and a simple object to store comments.

### HTML

```html
<!-- index.html -->

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Comment System</title>
</head>
<body>
    <!-- Post content -->
    <h2>Post Title</h2>
    <p>Post Content</p>

    <!-- Comment form -->
    <form id="comment-form">
        <input type="text" id="name" placeholder="Name">
        <textarea id="comment" placeholder="Comment"></textarea>
        <button type="submit">Submit</button>
    </form>

    <!-- Display comments -->
    <h2>Comments:</h2>
    <ul id="comments"></ul>

    <script src="script.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
```

### JavaScript

```javascript
// script.js

const commentForm = document.getElementById('comment-form');
const nameInput = document.getElementById('name');
const commentInput = document.getElementById('comment');
const commentsList = document.getElementById('comments');

class Comment {
    constructor(name, text) {
        this.name = name;
        this.text = text;
    }

    display() {
        const li = document.createElement('LI');
        li.innerHTML = `<strong>${this.name}:</strong> ${this.text}`;
        commentsList.appendChild(li);
    }
}

let postComments = [];

commentForm.addEventListener('submit', (e) => {
    e.preventDefault();
    const name = nameInput.value.trim();
    const commentText = commentInput.value.trim();

    if (name && commentText) {
        const newComment = new Comment(name, commentText);
        postComments.push(newComment);
        newComment.display();
        commentsList.scrollTop = commentsList.scrollHeight;

        // Clear input fields
        nameInput.value = '';
        commentInput.value = '';
    }
});
```

**Usage**

1. Save the HTML as `index.html` and JavaScript code as `script.js`.
2. Open `index.html` in a web browser.
3. Fill out the comment form with your name and comment.
4. Submit the form to add your comment.

Note: This is a simple example and does not include any server-side validation or storage for comments. In a real-world application, you would need to implement additional security measures, such as authentication and authorization, and store comments in a database using a framework like Node.js with Express.js or MongoDB.
